english:
  title: Preface to the Collection of Eastern Prose-Poetry in Paired Sentences
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer of the Wuyin year of the Later Zhiyuan era, I completed the compilation of Eastern Prose-Poetry in Paired Sentences. Upon careful reflection, our ancestral kingdom received investiture from the Middle Kingdom and maintained this succession through generations, never failing in reverence for Heaven's mandate and in the sincere practice of loyalty and humility toward the great state. Thus was the proper form of our memorials and proclamations established.

    Yet our court officials addressed their sovereign as 'Your Sagacity' or 'Your Majesty,' drawing comparisons above to Yao and Shun and below to the Han and Tang dynasties. The king himself would sometimes refer to himself as 'I' or 'the One,' issuing commands styled as 'Edicts' and 'Decrees,' proclaiming amnesties across the realm, and establishing offices and officials after the manner of the Middle Kingdom. Such practices, I confess, ventured far into presumption, astonishing all who witnessed them. Within China itself, such things would hardly merit concern. Yet for us, what harm could there be?

    Since our attachment to the Great Yuan, we have come to be regarded as one family. The titles of Province, Bureau, Court, and Ministry were long ago abandoned. Yet custom clung to old habits, and the affliction remained. During the Dade era, the Imperial Court sent the Administrator Qala-jishi to rectify these matters. Only then were we reformed anew, and none dared to perpetuate the old ways.

    In this present compilation, I have largely selected texts from before our subjugation. I fear that those encountering these for the first time may experience bewilderment and doubt. Therefore, I inscribe this preface as a guide.
  footnotes:
    - The Later Zhiyuan era (1335-1340) refers to the final years of the Yuan Dynasty under Toghon Temür.
    - The 'Eastern prose-poetry in paired sentences' (四六, siḷiu) refers to a literary form popular in East Asia characterized by antithetical couplets and ornate parallel structure.
    - The tension described reflects Korea's complex political position—nominally subordinate to Yuan China yet maintaining distinct sovereignty and cultural practices.
    - Qala-jishi (闊里吉思) was a Mongol administrator who helped reform Korean court ceremonial and administrative terminology during the Dade era (1307-1311).
